          <p class="model-list">MC30WS · MC30ES · MCES30 · MED301J</p>
          <p>Microwave + convection in one cavity. Popular over a wall oven for the "double cavity" feel in 30" rough openings. Separate control logic for microwave vs convection — some error codes (E2, E5) relate specifically to the microwave module.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <p class="footnote">Pre-Masterpiece legacy ovens (PSO, CMT, older C301) — we service when BSH parts distribution still has inventory. For some early-2000s models the factory no longer stocks thermostats and main controls, and we'll tell you on the phone whether it's serviceable or not.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ── WALL OVEN FOCUS ── -->
  <section class="section">
    <div class="container narrow">
      <p class="eyebrow-sub">Wall oven service</p>
      <h2>Wall oven repair — the built-in-specific approach</h2>
      <p>A Thermador wall oven sits in a cabinet opening cut to exact spec. Pulling it out is a last resort, not a default. Here's how we work through the common wall-oven failures without disturbing the cabinetry.</p>

      <div class="problem">
        <h3>Heating element replacement (bake or broil)</h3>
        <p>The bake element is at the bottom of the cavity, held by two screws through the rear wall and a two-pin electrical connector behind the oven. We remove the oven racks, unscrew the bake cover, disconnect the two terminals at the element, pull the old element out through the cavity front, and install the new one the reverse way. Total time: 45 minutes. The oven stays in the cabinet.</p>
        <p>Broil element is at the top of the cavity, same approach — two screws, two-pin connection, pulled out through the front. We replace both at the same visit if the oven is 10+ years old and one has already failed — second element failure within 18 months is a common pattern.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="problem">
        <h3>Door gasket replacement</h3>
        <p>The rubber gasket around the oven door seals the cavity heat. When it degrades — and it always does, around year 8 — preheating takes longer, baking is uneven, and the kitchen gets noticeably warmer during roasts. Replacement: pull the door off the hinges (about a minute per hinge if they release properly), peel the old gasket from the groove in the door frame, clean the channel, seat the new gasket with the correct orientation. 30-minute job, no cabinetry touched.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="problem">
        <h3>Door hinge failure or door misalignment</h3>
        <p>Door hinges are the wearing part on any oven that gets used. Thermador's SoftClose hinges have a damper spring that fails around year 10–12, and you'll notice the door slams shut instead of easing, or it sags when open. Replacement is both hinges at once (they wear together) — we remove the door, unscrew the hinge assemblies from the oven frame, install new hinges, rehang the door, and check the seal around the gasket. The replacement hinge set is one of the more expensive Thermador parts ($285–$420) but the job is an hour.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="problem">
        <h3>Convection fan motor</h3>
        <p>The convection fan lives behind the rear cavity wall. Access from inside the cavity: remove the cover plate, disconnect the wire leads, unbolt the motor from the rear wall. New motor comes with the blade already mounted. 60-minute job on most Masterpiece and Professional ovens. The oven stays in place. A grinding or humming fan has usually damaged the motor bearings — we don't repair bearings, we replace the assembly.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="problem">
        <h3>Self-clean cycle won't start or won't finish</h3>
        <p>Self-clean needs the door-latch motor to engage the pin that locks the door during high-temperature cleaning. If the latch motor fails, you get an E1 error (cleaner cycle disabled) and the door stays openable but the cycle won't run. If the latch engaged mid-cycle and now won't release, the oven is stuck locked — we bring a manual release tool. Latch motor replacement: access through the oven top cover, reach in from above, swap the motor. Takes about 40 minutes. We don't recommend running the self-clean cycle more than twice a year on any oven — it stresses every component.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="problem">
        <h3>Control board failure (E2, E3, E4 codes)</h3>
        <p>The main control board sits behind the front bezel above the door. Access: remove the bezel trim (two screws, clip fit), disconnect the ribbon cable and the power lead, unscrew the board mount. Total access time 20 minutes, and we have replacement boards on the truck for most Masterpiece and Professional models. E3 and E4 usually mean the control has stopped talking to the bake relay — could be the board, could be the relay harness. Diagnostic separates which is which.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ── COMBI-STEAM FOCUS ── -->
  <section class="section section-alt">
    <div class="container narrow">
      <p class="eyebrow-sub">Combi-steam specific</p>
      <h2>Thermador combi-steam: descaling, water system, generator</h2>
      <p>The MES and MED combi-steam ovens add a parallel water system to the standard wall oven architecture: reservoir, pump, steam generator, and a sensor stack that monitors water level, cavity condition, and rack cleanliness. Most calls we get on these are not part replacements — they're cleanup and sensor resets.</p>

      <div class="problem">
        <h3>"Refill water reservoir" message with a full tank</h3>
        <p>The water-level sensor in the reservoir gets fouled by mineral deposits from LA tap water, and it reads low even when the tank is full. Cleanup: empty the reservoir, clean the sensor contacts with distilled white vinegar on a soft cloth, refill with distilled or filtered water. If the message returns within a few weeks, the sensor needs replacement ($185). This is a common call — we've done it dozens of times.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="problem">
        <h3>"Clean cavity and refill tank" message that won't clear</h3>
        <p>This is the sensor stack asking you to run the descaling cycle, and sometimes it doesn't reset after you do. Manual reset: hold the Enter/OK button for 10 seconds with the door closed, or perform a full power cycle at the breaker for 60 seconds. If the message persists, the descale-residue sensor at the base of the cavity has scale buildup blocking the contact. We pull the sensor, clean it in descaling solution, reinstall. Takes 30 minutes.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="problem">
        <h3>Descaling cycle won't complete</h3>
        <p>The descaling cycle pumps a descaling solution through the steam generator and then rinses it out. Failure modes: descaling pump seized (rare, parts available), water inlet valve stuck closed (common, $145 part), or the cycle timing out because the generator isn't heating fast enough. Generator heating element failure is a real parts job — $485–$720 plus a 3-hour labor window. We verify it's the element, not a sensor, before ordering.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="problem">
        <h3>Steam oven runs cold</h3>
        <p>Either the generator heating element has failed, or the thermostat has drifted out of range, or the water isn't reaching the generator. Diagnostic checks generator voltage, element resistance, and line pressure in sequence. If the element is open-circuit, replacement is ordered (parts lead time 2–4 days from BSH distribution) and we schedule the return visit.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ── SPEED OVEN FOCUS ── -->
  <section class="section">
    <div class="container narrow">
      <p class="eyebrow-sub">Speed ovens (microwave combos)</p>
      <h2>Speed oven repair — MC30WS and the MC series</h2>
      <p>The Thermador speed oven combines microwave and convection in a single 30" wall cavity. Most installs pair it above a single wall oven for a "double-cavity" look that saves 4–6 inches of cabinet height versus a true double wall oven. The service picture is different from a plain wall oven because there are two heating systems — microwave and convection — each with its own control logic.</p>
      <p>Common calls:</p>
      <ul class="scope-list">
        <li><strong>Microwave module won't fire</strong> — magnetron fail, diode fail, or high-voltage capacitor. We test the HV circuit with a proper meter (homeowners should never open a microwave cavity without lockout — the HV capacitor holds charge after power-off). Replacement magnetrons run $280–$420.</li>
        <li><strong>Convection side works, microwave side E2 code</strong> — usually the microwave-specific control module, not the main board. Replacement is a module swap, not a full main-board job.</li>
        <li><strong>Convection fan runs continuously after cooking</strong> — designed cool-down cycle, but if it runs more than 15 minutes there's a temperature sensor drift preventing the control from seeing the cavity has cooled. Sensor replacement, $165.</li>
        <li><strong>Door interlock switches</strong> — three interlock switches check door-closed before microwave will run. If any one fails you get an E5 code or simply nothing happens when you press Start. Switches are inexpensive and we carry them.</li>
      </ul>
